<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-07-13T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-07-13T05:00:00-05:00" n="461" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d461">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BB Palestine/7–1348: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Childs</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-07-13T13:00:00+03:00">July 13,
                                    1948—1 p. m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>412. Legtel 406, 12th.<note n="1" xml:id="d461fn1">Not printed.</note>
                            British Ambassador states he received yesterday from <gloss target="#t_FO1">FO</gloss> verbal reply to his representations in
                            behalf SA acceptance prolongation truce. Reply characterized Bernadotte
                            proposals as being worse than <hi rend="italic">status quo ante</hi> but
                            said <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> would support with Arab states
                            acceptable prolongation. Trott said he had been authorized to make
                            strong representations including reminder that if Arabs rejected truce
                            and UN applied sanctions <gloss target="#t_HMG1">HMG</gloss> would be
                            unable to fulfill its arms commitments to Arab states.<note n="2" xml:id="d461fn2">Damascus, on July 12, reported a conversation with
                                the Syrian Acting Foreign Minister in which the latter insisted that
                                Count Bernadotte had proved himself pro-Zionist and that Syria would
                                never consent to an extension of the truce until the Mediator’s
                                absurd proposals had been scrapped. (Telegram 439, 501.BB
                                Palestine/7–1248)</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Pouched Arab capitals.</p>
                        <p>Sent Department 412, repeated London 124.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Childs</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>